{
  "answer": "**Few works in the corpus are structured as direct rhetorical addresses to a national or communal collective using first-person plural (\"we,\" \"our\") or equivalent second-person appeals to a shared group identity.**\n\n**Johann Gottlieb Fichte's *Zurückforderung der Denkfreiheit von den Fürsten Europens* (1793)** is explicitly framed as a speech to the \"peoples\" of Europe (particularly Germans), urging collective resistance to princely suppression of thought. It opens with direct second-person communal appeals: \"No, you peoples, give up everything... only this you must uphold,\"[^1] and \"The times of barbarism are over, you peoples.\"[^2] The preface targets \"the less instructed public\" for its influence on \"general opinion.\"[^3]\n\n**Allama Iqbal's *Bang-e-Dara* collections** (1924, Parts 1–3) contain poems explicitly invoking a Muslim communal/national \"we.\" \n\n- Part 1, Ch. 26 (*Hindustani Bachon Ka Qaumi Geet* / \"National Song of Indian Children\"): A communal anthem celebrating India as \"my homeland... this land of mine,\" tying shared history from Chishti, Nanak, Tatars, to Arabs.[^4]\n- Part 3, Ch. 13 (*Khitab ba Jawanan-e-Islam* / \"An Address to the Muslim Youth\"): Direct second-person address to \"O Muslim youth,\" contrasting their inaction with ancestors' world-conquering spirit: \"you are all talk, they were all action.\"[^5]\n- Part 3, Ch. 23 (*Tarana-e-Milli* / \"The Anthem of the Community\"): First-person plural Muslim ummah from \"Chin to Arab lands\": \"our story flows,\" \"our soul,\" \"we stand as guardians,\" \"we do not bow.\"[^6]\n\nNo other works—such as Charles Comte's property treatises (analytical prose on national territory),[^7] Charles Dunoyer's economic volumes, Cynewulf's Old English poems (narrative hagiography), or Indic smṛtis (legal codes)—are rhetorical addresses to a \"we.\" Searches for phrases like \"we the,\" \"our nation,\" and communal markers yielded no further matches.[^8]",
